The losers remain challengers
HARARE: Before the presidential elections this month, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and throughout southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get them.
Instead, they received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats from the party of Robert Mugabe, the African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terror is accounted for by the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
As a result of intimidation and violence, my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), was unable to reach the electorate in large parts of the rural areas.
Furthermore, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations in total, I believe that more than 360,000 people stood in line in Harare and Chitungwiza alone without being able to cast their ballots.
I still doubt the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from deploying observers at 52% of rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party was missing observers at 6 out of 10 rural polling stations.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to enforce their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were only controlled by ZANU supporters.
Even in this early stage of our investigation, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes were cast for Mugabe.
In light of the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent President Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is, in their eyes, illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe have been denied their right to freely and democratically choose their president.
The dispute over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined and deserve to have this recognized.
Perhaps it is not too late for that.
I am writing this text in sorrow, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
What also happens, I will stand by the people as a loyal servant and see this through with them.
Maybe the government will arrest me.
I was also arrested before the elections for treason.
In the worst-case scenario, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never break the will of the people, their rights, and their power.
It is in our hands to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow ourselves to be overwhelmed by despair.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be prepared to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I just ask the people of Zimbabwe to stay strong and finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who did not back down.
It is the heroes of a new Zimbabwe whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very rocky road together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve kindness and resilience.
I notice that the people of Zimbabwe are impatient.
I understand that.
But for a political process to exist, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply let these elections stand, but they must not fall for Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence either.
The people of Zimbabwe want legitimate change in the constitution, the legal system, and they will achieve it, despite all the obstacles.
We know we are not alone.
We know that election rigging occurs throughout Africa.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and scandals seem to be a norm during elections.
There is always a crisis somewhere in Africa due to elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it's time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can still hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in their hour of greatest need.
I promise not to abandon them.
